30rassi maturitatem: maturitas significa the full, all-round development oi mental powers and hence is used as a synonym of ‘perfectus' See Cic. Brut. 92, 318 (cited c. 22 10) and note c. 3 12. The same epithet is applied to Crassus by Macrob. Vl, 16 sunt stili dicendi duo . . .nnus est runcinus et gravis, qualis Crasso adsi- gnatur. May not this be a reminiscence of the present passage? Crassus is at least not elsewhere in extant writers so desig· nated. —calamistros Maecenatis: calamistri, literally ‘ouding- irons or crisping-pins.² The expression, in the figurative sense oi ‘rhetorical flonrishes’ is borrowed from Cicero who uses it twice: Brut. 75, 262 qui volent illa (sc. Caesaris commentarios) calamistris inurere Orat. 23, ta ne calamistri quidem adhibebuntur (sc. ora tioni), where see Sandys' note. On the effeminate and florid style of Maecenas, cf. Suet. 4 tinnitus Gallionis: L. Iunias Gallio, the friend of Ovid and of Seneca Rhetor, and the judge who presided at the trial of St. Paul, was the author of a rhetorical treatise (Quint. III 1, 21) and ‘declamationes' from which Seneca has preserved numerous speci· mens cp. Teuffel, a. L. § 268, t. These cannot, of course, either confirm or disprove Messalla's urrfavorable criticism‚ as is clear ’ from a remark in Sen. Contr. III praef. 18 ext. Gallio’s enduring reputation seems to be attested, however, by Apoll. Sid. Ep. V 10 who predicates ‘gravitas' of him and by a passage in Hieronymus cited c. 26 32. —tinaitus ¹ jingling style’ In this figurative sense, the word is ἄπ. etp„ but its analogue ‘tinnulus' occurs once in Hieron.
